[{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = AwesomeEquations","category":"page"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for AwesomeEquations.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Modules = [AwesomeEquations]","category":"page"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations.Dual","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations.Dual","text":"Dual(a, b)\n\nDual number with value a and derivative b.\n\nA dual number x = a + b epsilon is defined such that epsilon^2 = 0 and f(a + b epsilon) = f(a) + f(a) b epsilon for all f. The derivative of a function is thus given by f(a) = y when f(a + epsilon) = x + y epsilon.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations.finite_diff-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations.finite_diff","text":"finite_diff(f, x; h = sqrt(eps(typeof(x))))\n\nCompute the derivative of f at x using a central finite difference (second order).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations.forward_diff-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations.forward_diff","text":"forward_diff(f, x)\n\nCompute the derivative of f at x using forward mode automatic differention (with dual numbers).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations.forward_euler","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations.forward_euler","text":"forward_euler(f, p, u₀, T, Δt = 0.1)\n\nSolve ODE dudt = f(u p t) with forward Euler, where p are parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#AwesomeEquations.rk4","page":"Home","title":"AwesomeEquations.rk4","text":"rk4(f, p, u₀, T, Δt = 0.1)\n\nSolve ODE dudt = f(u p t) with RK4, where p are parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
